post_text:
State Broadband Office needs you to help identify low or no high-speed internet service areas.

The Washington State Broadband Office and state Public Works Board have launched a mapping initiative to identify gaps in high-speed internet service and areas of broadband infrastructure needs in order to advance the state’s goal to have universal broadband access in Washington by 2024.

The first step is for Washington residents to perform a one-minute access and speed survey found at broadband.wa.gov. Using the easy-to-follow instructions and a simple link, anyone can complete the speed test at home using any computer or mobile device.

Those with no internet access at their homes are encouraged to visit a local library or drive-in hotspot in their community, or use their mobile device to take the survey and check the “no available service” button to record their physical address. This simple access and speed survey will result in statistically valid data and mapping for decision makers to plot a course for Washington’s ambitious broadband expansion plans.

post_text:
An update from Mr. Gummel, Superintendent:

Dear Pioneer Families,

I am sure that by now many of you have heard the news that Governor Inslee has closed all private and public schools in Snohomish, King and Pierce Counties.

I want to reassure families that our paramount duty is to ensure the safety of our students, staff and community. We are closely monitoring this changing situation and are continuing to closely partner with our local and state agencies. At this time, there has not been guidance to close schools in Mason County.

Tomorrow morning there will be a conference with state leaders and superintendents, where I expect to receive additional information and direction. I will update families, staff and the community as more information becomes available.

Please feel free to reach out to your school principals or the district office with additional questions.

Thank you for all of your support.

We are closely monitoring this changing situation and are continuing to closely partner with our local and state agencies. At this time, there has not been guidance to close schools in Mason County.

Tomorrow morning there will be a conference with state leaders and superintendents, where I expect to receive additional information and direction. I will update families, staff and the community as more information becomes available.

Please feel free to reach out to your school principals or the district office with additional questions.

Thank you for all of your support.

shared_text:
Shelton High School
February 7 at 1:39 PM ·

On November 20th, DECA officers Abby Akin and Audrey Beaudoin had the unique opportunity to present to the Washington State Senate Committee on Early Learning & K-12 Education. Audrey spoke about her experience in the after school program at Pioneer, highlighting Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (STEM) activities. Abby, also a Pioneer student, focused on the leadership aspect of the after school program and how she has had the opportunity to pay it forward creating student-led activities, such as the Olympic Middle School (OMS) Financial Reality Fair and the Entrepreneur Showcase, that she and her DECA chapter put on for OMS students. The girls did a great job and received a certificate for their time and efforts.

February 7 at 1:39 PM ·

Audrey spoke about her experience in the after school program at Pioneer, highlighting Science, Technology, Engineering, and Math (STEM) activities. Abby, also a Pioneer student, focused on the leadership aspect of the after school program and how she has had the opportunity to pay it forward creating student-led activities, such as the Olympic Middle School (OMS) Financial Reality Fair and the Entrepreneur Showcase, that she and her DECA chapter put on for OMS students. The girls did a great job and received a certificate for their time and efforts.

Pioneer Middle School 402
September 5, 2019 at 6:16 AM ·

Key information from Pioneer Middle School:

1. Most students have received supplies for their AVID binder. This includes a 3-inch binder, dividers, notebooks, etc. This is a key item that they will use daily and comes home. Please make sure that your child returns to school with these supplies daily. Losing or forgetting these supplies could impact your child's ability to be fully engaged and successful in their classes.

2. Please make sure that you are communicating if your child is riding the bus being picked up. When they are unsure then action must occur in the last minute to help them identify how they are getting home which holds up the departure of the bus and other students timely commutes home.

Thank you for your support.

Pioneer Middle School 402
September 3, 2019 at 8:32 PM ·

Good evening Pioneer families,

The first day of school begins tomorrow with doors opening at 8:10 am. We are excited to have all of our returning Eagle students for the 2019-20 school year. Staff have been hard at work getting their rooms and school ready for all of our great kids.

A couple of notes and highlights as we begin the school year.

1. Every Wednesday including tomorrow is an early release at 2:00 pm.

2. Beginnig this year, all changes for the bus must be communicated by 1:00 pm that day of the change so please plan accordingly.

3. As an AVID school all students will be provided a binder and supplies that will be used in all classes. These supplies will be coming home almost daily. Please work with your child to make sure they have these items daily and not left at home or misplaced as it is a big part of their expectations for all classes.

Again, we are excited for the new year and can not wait to see all of you.

Go Eagles!

Good evening Pioneer families,

The first day of school begins tomorrow with doors opening at 8:10 am. We are excited to have all of our returning Eagle students for the 2019-20 school year. Staff have been hard at work getting their rooms and school ready for all of our great kids.

A couple of notes and highlights as we begin the school year.

1. Every Wednesday including tomorrow is an early release at 2:00 pm.

2. Beginnig this year, all changes for the bus must be communicated by 1:00 pm that day of the change so please plan accordingly.

3. As an AVID school all students will be provided a binder and supplies that will be used in all classes. These supplies will be coming home almost daily. Please work with your child to make sure they have these items daily and not left at home or misplaced as it is a big part of their expectations for all classes.

Again, we are excited for the new year and can not wait to see all of you.

Go Eagles!

September 3, 2019 at 3:54 PM ·

Good Afternoon Pioneer Families,

We are so excited to start our first day of school tomorrow, September 4th. School starts at 8:30 am. Remember, every Wednesday is our Professional Development and we dismiss at 2:00 pm.

Here are 3 key points for this school year:

1. On Monday, Tuesday, Thursday, and Friday, students will be dismissed at 3:00 pm. On Wednesdays, our dismissal is at 2:00 pm.

2. We will take changes in students after school plans until 1:00 pm. Please make sure to call the front office prior to 1:00 pm.

3. If you plan on picking up your student, please remember we will ask for ID. If you would like a pick up pass, please fill out the paperwork with the front desk.

Remember, Kindergarten starts September 9th. We are looking forward to a great school year.

post_text:
Dearest Pioneer Community,

It is with bitter-sweet sentiment that we announce some changes at Pioneer Elementary School for this upcoming 2019-20 school year. Mrs. Jodi Schaefer has resigned her position as school principal and accepted another position closer to home. We will miss her energy and support of our students and staff. It is then, with great excitement, that we announce Mrs. Amy Koster, former Assistant Principal at Pioneer Elementary, as the new Principal. Mrs. Koster has strong passions and beliefs for student learning and engagement, developing and strengthening effective teaching practices, and working closely with our Pioneer families and community. She will do an excellent job in serving all our students, staff, and families. When you get a chance, feel free to wish them both success and wellness in their next professional journey. Enjoy the remainder of your summer and we sincerely look forward to seeing all our families and students at Open House Thursday, August 29th and our first day of school, Wednesday, September 4, 2019

post_text:
OUR GIRLS WERE FOUND SAFE
Pioneer School District is happy to report that the two girls who were reported missing have been located. Superintendent Gummel commends the entire staff of Pioneer who searched the woods and roads for the two young students following word of their absence. Parents and family members who gathered in the District Office were elated at the news of finding the missing youth. Superintendent Gummel appreciates all the support from the local sheriff department who came alongside the families and school district in locating and securing the safety of the two young ladies. If you have any additional questions or concerns, please don't hesitate to reach out to the District Office.

Attention parents or Guardians of 8th grade students:

Wednesday, January 30, 2019, at 5:00 PM, Pioneer Middle School will be hosting a parent question and answer session for all 8th-grade students transitioning to Shelton High School for the 2019-2020 school year. This is a great opportunity to hear from Shelton High School administration, as well as Freshman academy staff, to answer any questions you may have.
Emails and a phone call will be going out to all 8th grade families beginning this evening at 5:30 PM to notify you of the upcoming event.
If you have any questions please feel free to contact the Pioneer Middle School Office 360-426-8291 -or-
Shelton High School office 360-426-4471

Sheriff Salisbury, Dana Rosenbach and Marty Brewer talk school safety

IFIBERONE News Radio - KMAS
March 5, 2018 at 2:25 PM ·

VIDEO - In a two-part conversation during the Mason County Sheriff's Office Visit, now sponsored by Our Community Credit Union, Sheriff Salisbury started by responding to Mason County Commissioner Randy Neatherlin's proposal for school resource officers. In the second half of the conversation Sheriff Salisbury was joined by the North Mason School Superintendent Dana Rosenbach and the Pioneer School Superintendent Marty Brewer about work that's been done to keep the schools safe and possible future work being done.
The Mason County Sheriffs Office Visit is sponsored by Our Community Credit Union

Seattle's acclaimed 5th Avenue Theatre brought its Adventure Musical Theatre Touring Comping to Pioneer Elementary for a special performance of a new musical, "Rosie the Riveter." The show tells the story of the heroic women in the World War II workforce who built the airplanes that helped win the war, known collectively as "Rosie the Riverters."

Thank you 5th Avenue Theatre.
